s the migrants' strategies for economic success in the diaspora, for preserving their heritage, and for resisting British mandate legislation, including citizenship rejections meted out to thousands of Palestinian migrants. They did this in newspapers, social and cultural clubs and associations, political organizations and committees, and in hundreds of petitions and pleas delivered to local and international governing bodies demanding justice for Palestinian migrants barred from Palestinian citizenship. As this book shows, Palestinian political consciousness developed as a thoroughly transnational process in the first half of the twentieth century—and the first articulation of a Palestinian right of return emerged well before 1948.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCitizenshipzPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 0aPalestinian ArabsxEthnic identityxHistoryy20th century. 0aPalestinian ArabsxLegal status, laws, etc.zPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 0aPalestinian ArabszLatin AmericaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPalestinian ArabszLatin AmericaxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aTransnationalismxPolitical aspectszPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh  aBritish Mandate.  aCitizenship.  aDiaspora.  aLatin America.  aMigration.  aOttoman Empire.  aPalestine.  aPeriodicals.  aPetitions.  aRight of Return.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363227140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503632271423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503632271/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles